\h Yob
\toc1 Iyyov (Job)
\toc2 Iyyov
\toc3 Iyyov
\mt1 Iyyov
\mt2 (Job)
\is1 Introduction
\ip \bk The account of Iyyov\bk* (but commonly as known as вҖҳJobвҖҷ which is the English evolution of the Germanic adaptation of the Greek adaptation бјёПҺОІ (IЕҚb) of his actual Hebrew name вҖҳЧҗЦҙЧҷЦјЧ•Ц№Ч‘вҖҷ) is an account about a godly man who was struck by a series of tragedies: all his children and their families were killed, all his extensive wealth was lost, and then he was struck with a terrible disease. By means of this seven-part account, the reader is informed about how Iyyov and his friends react concerning those tragedies. Then finally, God reveals himself to Iyyov and the others.
\ip Near the beginning of this document, God is told by Satan that it's not good governing of his people if he always rewards those who obey him. What if people only obey God because they're after the material blessings that would always follow. This would mean that their obedience no longer comes from their hearts. Yes, that's what Satan said about Iyyov, so God allowed Satan to test Iyyov's heart to see if he'd continue to trust God in times of suffering and misery.
\ip Iyyov's traditional friends assumed that he must be suffering because he sinned. Surely he wouldn't suffer all that if he'd been honest and righteous. None of them could understand why God might allow sickness or disease to strike someone if he was truly a righteous person, but this is too simplistic for Iyyov to accept. Therefore he challenges God to present his case. In all of that, Iyyov's faith in God isn't lost, but he desires to regain his honour as an honest and godly person.
\ip God doesn't answer Iyyov's questions but he responds by displaying his own power and wisdom and knowledge. So then Iyyov acknowledges God as the wise creator and requests forgiveness for his angry words.
\ip The final segment of this account explains how Iyyov was restored to health, peace, and prosperity (all the elements of вҖҳshalomвҖҷ/вҖҳЧ©ЦёЧҒЧңЧ•Ц№ЧқвҖҷ), and how he actually prospered even more than before. It also shows how God was angry at Iyyov's friends, because they had so much to say when none of them actually knew why Iyyov had sufferedвҖ”only Iyyov had really sensed that God and his eventual (but eternal) justice is greater than simplistic proverbs and trite beliefs.
\iot Main components of this account
\io1 SECTION ONE: Introduction \ior 1:1вҖ“2:13\ior*
\io1 SECTION TWO: Dialogues between Iyyov and his friends \ior 3:1вҖ“27:23\ior*
\io2 a. Iyyov's complaint \ior 3:1-26\ior*
\io2 b. The first dialogue \ior 4:1вҖ“14:22\ior*
\io2 c. The second dialogue \ior 15:1вҖ“21:34\ior*
\io2 d. The third dialogue \ior 22:1вҖ“27:23\ior*
\io1 SECTION THREE: Praising wisdom \ior 28:1-28\ior*
\io1 SECTION FOUR: Iyyov's final statement \ior 29:1вҖ“31:40\ior*
\io1 SECTION FIVE: Elihu's speech \ior 32:1вҖ“37:24\ior*
\io1 SECTION SIX: God answers Iyyov \ior 38:1вҖ“42:6\ior*
\io1 SECTION SEVEN: The final restoration \ior 42:7-17\ior*
\rem This is still a very early look into the unfinished text of the Open English Translation of the Bible. Please double-check the text in advance before using in public.
\ie
\c 1
\ms1 SECTION ONE: The introduction
\mr (1:1вҖ“2:13)
\s1 Iyyov's prosperous life
\rem /s1 Prologue; Job and His Family; Satan Tests Job
\p
\v 1 \add Once\add* there was a man called IyyovВҰ232252 \add (Job)\add* who lived inВҰ232249 the UzВҰ232251 regionВҰ232249. \add He\add* was blamelessВҰ232258 and righteousвҖ”both obeying GodВҰ232261 and avoiding evil.
\v 2 He had sevenВҰ232267 sonsВҰ232268 andВҰ232269 threeВҰ232269 daughtersВҰ232270,
\v 3 and he owned 7,000 sheepВҰ232277, 3,000 camelsВҰ232280, 1,000 cattle, and 500 donkeysВҰ232288, as well as many slaves. Iyyov was \add richer\add* than \add anyone else\add* who lived in the area east \add of the Jordan River\add*.
\v 4 \add Iyyov's\add* sonsВҰ232303 \add regularly\add* held feasts in theirВҰ232312 homes, and whenever any of them held a feast, he would inviteВҰ232310 all his brothers and sistersВҰ232312 to share the meal with him.
\v 5 \add ThenВҰ232318 once a feastВҰ232322 was over\add*, Iyyov would send \add for his children\add* and consecrate themвҖ”he got up earlyВҰ232326 in the morningВҰ232327 and offered burntВҰ232329 offerings for each of them, because Iyyov said, вҖңPerhaps my \add children\add* have sinnedВҰ232336 and cursed\f + \fr 1:15 \ft Literally вҖҳblessedвҖҷ but it's possible that the original reading was вҖҳcursedвҖҷ and that scribes changed it to вҖҳblessedвҖҷ in order to avoid the uncomfortable concept of a person cursing God. Traditional manuscripts of the Hebrew Bible don't have a marginal notation about this (as they do in the case of 7:20), but LXX uses вҖҳбјҗОҪОөОҪОҝО®ОёО·ПғОұОҪ ОәОұОәО¬вҖҷ which can be rendered as вҖҳhave thought evil thingsвҖҷ and the Peshitta (Syriac) uses вҖҳreviledвҖҷ. Many other translations also use вҖҳcursedвҖҷ since this is the kind of change that scribes are known to have made in similar cases.\f* GodВҰ232339 in theirВҰ232340 heartsВҰ232340.вҖқ \add вүҲIt was Job's regular habit to\add* \add intercede for his children\add*.
\s1 Satan's first attack on Iyyov
\rem /s1 Attack on Job's Character; Job's First Test
\p
\v 6 It was the dayВҰ232350 that God's sonsВҰ232352\f + \fr 1:6 \ft It's not clear from the text who these are.\f* came to presentВҰ232354 themselvesВҰ232354 to YahwehВҰ232357, and the adversaryВҰ232361 (Satan) was also there amongВҰ232362 them.\x + \xo 1:6: \xt Gen 6:2.\x*
\v 7 YahwehВҰ232365 asked him, вҖңWhere have youВҰ232370 just come from?вҖқ
\p вҖңI have come from the earthВҰ232378, whereВҰ232369 I was travelling aroundВҰ232379 \add to see what was going onВҰ232380\add*.вҖқ Satan replied.
\p
\v 8 вҖңHave youВҰ232387 \add noticed\add* my servantВҰ232391 IyyovВҰ232392?вҖқ YahwehВҰ232383 asked. вҖңThere's no one else like himВҰ232395 on the \add whole\add* earthВҰ232396вҖ”a blamelessВҰ232398 and righteous manВҰ232397 who obeys me GodВҰ232401 and avoids \add anything\add* evilВҰ232403.вҖқ
\p
\v 9 вҖңDoes IyyovВҰ232413 \add get\add* nothingВҰ232411 \add back\add* for respecting GodВҰ232414?вҖқ Satan answeredВҰ232405 YahwehВҰ232409.
\v 10 вҖңDon't you \add constantly protect\add* him and his householdВҰ232424 and everythingВҰ232431 that's his? You've blessedВҰ232434 \add what he works on\add*, and his \add livestockВҰ232435 have multiplied prolifically\add*.
\v 11 However, just stretchВҰ232440 out your handВҰ232443 andВҰ232439 \add ruin\add* everything he has, thenВҰ232439 \add we'll see that\add* he'll curseВҰ232456 youВҰ232456 to your faceВҰ232455.вҖқ
\p
\v 12 вҖңListen, \add I'll cede you control over\add* everything he has,вҖқ Yahweh replied. вҖңOnly \add just\add* don'tВҰ232472 do \add anything\add* against \add Iyyov himself\add*.вҖқ \add SoВҰ232458\add* the adversary wentВҰ232476 away from Yahweh's \add presenceВҰ232479\add*.
\s1 Satan destroys Iyyov's wealth and children
\rem /s1 Job Loses Property and Children; Job's Children and Wealth Are Destroyed
\p
\v 13 \add SoВҰ232482 one\add* dayВҰ232483 when \add Iyyov's\add* sonsВҰ232484 and his daughtersВҰ232485 were eatingВҰ232486 and drinkingВҰ232487 wine in theirВҰ232490 eldest brother'sВҰ232490 houseВҰ232489,
\v 14 a messengerВҰ232493 cameВҰ232494 to IyyovВҰ232497 and \add reported\add*, вҖң\add While\add* the oxen were plowingВҰ232501 and the donkeysВҰ232502 were feeding \add nearby\add*,
\v 15 the SabeansВҰ232509 attackedВҰ232508 with their swordsВҰ232517 andВҰ232508 stole them \add all\add*. They killed all your slaves except that I \add managed to\add* escapeВҰ232518 to tell you.вҖқ
\p
\v 16 \add While\add* he was still speakingВҰ232529, another \add messenger\add* cameВҰ232531 and saidВҰ232532, вҖңThe fireВҰ232533 of GodВҰ232534 fell from the sky and burntВҰ232539 up the sheepВҰ232540 and the \add shepherds\add*. \add Only ashes are left\add*, except that I aloneВҰ232547 escapedВҰ232543 to tell you.вҖқ
\p
\v 17 \add While\add* he was still speakingВҰ232554, another \add one\add* cameВҰ232556 and \add explained\add*, вҖңThe Chaldeans formedВҰ232559 into threeВҰ232561 bands and \add raided\add* the camelsВҰ232566 and tookВҰ232567 them, and they attacked the slaves with their swordsВҰ232574, and I'm the only one who escapedВҰ232575 to \add come and\add* tell you.вҖқ
\p
\v 18 \add While\add* he was still speakingВҰ232585, another \add messenger\add* cameВҰ232587 and saidВҰ232588, вҖңYour sonsВҰ232589 and daughtersВҰ232590 were eatingВҰ232591 and drinkingВҰ232592 wine in the houseВҰ232594 of theirВҰ232595 eldest brotherВҰ232595
\v 19 when \add suddenly\add* a \add freak\add* windВҰ232599 cameВҰ232601 from acrossВҰ232603 the desert and struckВҰ232605 the houseВҰ232608. It \add collapsed\add* onВҰ232606 the youngВҰ232612 peopleВҰ232612 and \add killed them\add*, and only I aloneВҰ232618 have escapedВҰ232614 to tell you.вҖқ
\p
\v 20 Then IyyovВҰ232623 stood up and tore his robeВҰ232627 and shavedВҰ232628 his headВҰ232631. Then he knelt with his face to the ground and worshippedВҰ232634 \add God\add*,
\v 21 saying, вҖңI cameВҰ232638 naked from my mother'sВҰ232641 womb, and I will \add leave this life\add* naked. Yahweh gaveВҰ232647, and Yahweh has takenВҰ232649. May Yahweh's \add reputation???\add* be blessedВҰ232653.вҖқ
\p
\v 22 \add Through\add* all of that, IyyovВҰ232661 didn'tВҰ232658 \add disobey\add* GodВҰ232666 or \add accuse him of being evil\add*.
\c 2
\s1 Satan's second attack on Iyyov
\rem /s1 Job's Second Test; Attack on Job's Health; Satan Tests Job Again
\p
\v 1 It was the dayВҰ232670 that God's sonsВҰ232672 came to present themselvesВҰ232674 to YahwehВҰ232677 and the adversaryВҰ232681 (Satan) was also there amongВҰ232682 them.
\v 2 вҖңWhere have you come from?вҖқ YahwehВҰ232689 \add asked\add* the adversary.
\p вҖңFrom wandering on the earthВҰ232703 and going back and forth on it,вҖқ \add he\add* answeredВҰ232696.
\p
\v 3 вҖңHave you \add noticed\add* my servantВҰ232716 IyyovВҰ232717 \add (Job)\add*?вҖқ YahwehВҰ232708 asked Satan, вҖңbecause there'sВҰ232719 no one like him onВҰ232731 the earthВҰ232721вҖ”a blamelessВҰ232723 and righteous manВҰ232722, \add striving to obey\add* GodВҰ232726 and turning from evilВҰ232728. And he's stillВҰ232729 holding firmly to his integrityВҰ232731, even though you incitedВҰ232732 me against him, to \add ruin\add* him for nothing.вҖқ
\p
\v 4 вҖңSkinВҰ232741 for skin,вҖқ replied the adversaryВҰ232738, вҖң\add actually, a person will giveВҰ232750 everything they have to save their\add* lifeВҰ232752.
\v 5 However, just \add reach out\add* and touchВҰ232759 his fleshВҰ232765 and bonesВҰ232762, \add and see\add* if heВҰ232772 doesn't curseВҰ232772 youВҰ232772 to your faceВҰ232771.вҖқ
\p
\v 6 вҖң\add Listen\add*,вҖқ YahwehВҰ232775 saidВҰ232774 to \add him\add*, вҖң\add I'll give you powerВҰ232780 over him\add*, butВҰ232774 you \add must\add* preserveВҰ232785 his lifeВҰ232784.вҖқ
\p
\v 7 SoВҰ232793 the adversaryВҰ232788 wentВҰ232787 away from Yahweh'sВҰ232791 \add presenceВҰ232790\add*, andВҰ232787 he \add infected\add* IyyovВҰ232795 withВҰ232796 badВҰ232797 boils from the sole of his footВҰ232799 to \add the top of his headВҰ232802\add*.
\v 8 \add Iyyov picked up a piece of broken pottery\add* to \add scratch\add* himselfВҰ232808 with \add as\add* he sat \add down\add* in the middleВҰ232812 of a pile of ashesВҰ232814.
\p
\v 9 вҖңAre youВҰ232819 stillВҰ232819 holding tightly onto yourВҰ232821 integrityВҰ232821?вҖқ his wife \add asked\add* him. вҖң\add Just\add* curse GodВҰ232823 andВҰ232824 dieВҰ232824.вҖқ
\p
\v 10 вҖңYou're talkingВҰ232831 like a foolishВҰ232830 \add person\add*,вҖқ Iyyov \add вүҲreplied\add*. вҖңShould we \add only\add* accept good from GodВҰ232838 andВҰ232826 not receive the bad?вҖқ In all of that, Iyyov didn'tВҰ232842 sin \add inВҰ232851 what he said\add*.
\s1 Iyyov's three friends come
\rem /s1 Job's Friends Come; Job's Three Friends Share His Anguish; Job's Three Friends
\p
\v 11 \add When\add* Iyyov's threeВҰ232855 friendsВҰ232857 heardВҰ232854 \add about all the troublesВҰ232862 thatВҰ232864 had happened to\add* him, they each cameВҰ232866 from his placeВҰ232868: ElifazВҰ232869 from TemanВҰ232870, BildadВҰ232871 from Shuah, and ZofarВҰ232873 from NaamahВҰ232874. They gathered togetherВҰ232876 to comeВҰ232864 to consoleВҰ232878 and comfortВҰ232881 him.
\v 12 \add butВҰ232883 when\add* they saw him from a distanceВҰ232887, they \add barely\add* recognisedВҰ232889 him. They \add wailed loudly\add*, and they \add ripped their own clothes\add*, and they threwВҰ232896 dust \add into the air so that it would fall\add* on their headsВҰ232900. \add (All three of those were traditional signs of mourning.)\add*
\v 13 ThenВҰ232903 they sat with him \add thereВҰ232910\add* on the groundВҰ232905 for seven daysВҰ232907 andВҰ232903 seven nightsВҰ232909 without saying a \add single\add* wordВҰ232914 to \add Iyyov\add* because they had seen that \add his\add* sufferingВҰ232920 was extreme.
\c 3
\ms1 SECTION TWO: Iyyov talking with his friends
\mr (3:1вҖ“27:33)
\s1 Iyyov's complaint
\rem /s1 Job's Complaint to God; Job Speaks; Job's First Speech; Job Curses the Day He Was Born; Job's complaint to God
\p
\v 1 AfterВҰ232923 that, IyyovВҰ232927 spoke up andВҰ232931 cursedВҰ232931 \add the\add* dayВҰ232934 \add of\add* his \add conception\add*.\x + \xo 3:1-19: \xt Jer 20:14-18.\x*
\p
\v 2 HeВҰ232938 saidВҰ232939:
\q1
\v 3 May the dayВҰ232942 on which I was born perishВҰ232941,
\q1 andВҰ232946 the nightВҰ232946 thatВҰ232944 saidВҰ232947, вҖҳA boy has been conceivedВҰ232948.вҖҷ
\q1
\v 4 May that dayВҰ232951 be dark.
\q1 May GodВҰ232958 not search for it from aboveВҰ232959
\q2 and may no light shineВҰ232962 on it.
\q1
\v 5 May darknessВҰ232967 and a dark shadowВҰ232968 claim it.
\q1 вүҲMay a cloudВҰ232972 remain over it.
\q1 May the blacknesses of the dayВҰ232975 terrifyВҰ232973 it.
\q1
\v 6 May gloomВҰ232980 takeВҰ232979 that nightВҰ232977.
\q1 May it not be happy amongВҰ232984 the daysВҰ232984 of the yearВҰ232985.
\q1 May it not enter into the numberВҰ232986 of monthsВҰ232987.
\q1
\v 7 Listen, may that nightВҰ232993 be barrenВҰ232996.
\q1 May a happy shout never enter it.
\q1
\v 8 MayВҰ233009 those who curse days, curse that oneвҖ”
\q1 \add yes,\add* those \add people\add* who are skillful enough to wake up the large sea monster.
\q1
\v 9 May the starsВҰ233012 of its twilightВҰ233013 be dark.
\q1 May it stay waiting for the lightВҰ233016 that never \add arrives\add*.
\q1 May it not see the dawn \add breaking\add*.
\q1
\v 10 Because itВҰ233027 didn'tВҰ233026 close the doorsВҰ233028 of my \add mother's\add* womb,
\q1 to hide the sorrow from my eyesВҰ233032.
\b
\q1
\v 11 Why didn'tВҰ233035 I dieВҰ233037 \add at birthВҰ233036\add*?
\q1 вүҲ\add Just\add* come out then stop breathing?
\q1
\v 12 Why was I accepted onto \add her lap\add*?
\q1 вүҲAnd onto those breastsВҰ233047 to suckle?
\q1
\v 13 \add Yes,\add* I'd be peacefullyВҰ233055 lying down now.
\q1 вүҲI would have sleptВҰ233056 andВҰ233055 been at rest,
\q1
\v 14 along with kingsВҰ233064 andВҰ233065 counsellorsВҰ233065 of the earthВҰ233066вҖ”
\q1 \add yes,\add* thoseВҰ233067 who built monuments for themselvesВҰ233069.
\q1
\v 15 Or \add been asleep\add* with princesВҰ233074 \add and their\add* goldВҰ233075вҖ”
\q1 thoseВҰ233077 who filledВҰ233077 their housesВҰ233078 with silverВҰ233079.
\q1
\v 16 I might never have beenвҖ”like a stillbornВҰ233083 childВҰ233083.
\q1 вүҲLike some infantsВҰ233087 who never see the lightВҰ233091.
\q1
\v 17 Wicked \add people\add* don't cause any more trouble there.
\q1 Those who've run out of strengthВҰ233100 rest there.
\q1
\v 18 Prisoners are able to relax together.
\q1 They no longer hearВҰ233106 the voiceВҰ233107 of their taskmasterВҰ233108.
\q1
\v 19 Ordinary and famous \add people are all\add* alike thereВҰ233112.
\q1 And slavesВҰ233114 \add there\add* no longer have \add to obey their\add* mastersВҰ233116.
\b
\q1
\v 20 Why is lightВҰ233121 given to \add those\add* who are miserableВҰ233120?
\q1 вүҲAnd why's lifeВҰ233122 \add given to those\add* who are bitterВҰ233123 inside?
\q1
\v 21 They wish for deathВҰ233127 butВҰ233128 it won'tВҰ233128 come.\x + \xo 3:21: \xt Rev 9:6.\x*
\q1 They dig for it more than for hiddenВҰ233130 treasureВҰ233130.
\q1
\v 22 ThoseВҰ233137 who are happy for happiness sake,
\q1 will celebrate when they find the graveВҰ233140.
\q1
\v 23 \add Why search for\add* a path that's hiddenВҰ233146
\q2 when GodВҰ233148 has hedgedВҰ233147 them in?
\b
\q1
\v 24 Sighing has \add become more important\add* than eating.
\q1 вүҲMy groansВҰ233159 \add just\add* pour out like waterВҰ233158.
\q1
\v 25 I had my fears and they've \add come to pass\add*.
\q1 вүҲWhat I dreaded has come to me.
\q1
\v 26 I'm not relaxed or peacefulВҰ233174.
\q1 вүҲI can'tВҰ233173 rest \add because only\add* trouble comesВҰ233178.
\c 4
\s1 Elifaz's first response to Iyyov
\rem /s1 The First Dialogue; Eliphaz; Eliphaz's First Response to Job; Eliphaz Speaks: Job Has Sinned; First cycle of speeches
\sr (4:1вҖ“14:22)
\p
\v 1 Then ElifazВҰ233183 (from TemanВҰ233184) \add вүҲrepliedВҰ233182\add*:
\q1
\v 2 If \add someoneВҰ233187\add* tries \add to talk\add* withВҰ233192 you, will it wear you out?
\q1 \add ButВҰ233191\add* who can resist \add answering\add*?
\q1
\v 3 Listen, you've instructedВҰ233197 many \add other people\add*.
\q1 And you've \add encouraged those who were\add* weak.
\q1
\v 4 Your wordsВҰ233206 have encouraged those who were stumblingВҰ233203.
\q1 You've strengthenedВҰ233209 \add those\add* whose kneesВҰ233207 were buckling.
\q1
\v 5 ButВҰ233216 now it's you \add in trouble\add* and you're \add depressed\add*.
\q1 \add Troubles\add* touch you and you're discouraged.
\q1
\v 6 Doesn't your \add faith\add* give you confidenceВҰ233223?
\q1 \add What about\add* your hope and your integrityВҰ233225?
\q1
\v 7 RememberВҰ233228: Who has \add ever\add* perishedВҰ233234 when theyВҰ233237 were innocentВҰ233233?\f + \fr 4:7 \ft Don't forget that this is Elifaz giving his opinions and advice, and not necessarily endorsed as theologically sound. See God's disapproval of the words of Elifaz and his companions in Job 42:7-8.\f*
\q1 Or when were godly people \add ever\add* destroyedВҰ233237?
\b
\q1
\v 8 Just like I'veВҰ233240 seenВҰ233240 thoseВҰ233241 who plant evil andВҰ233243 sow mischiefВҰ233244 harvestВҰ233245 itВҰ233245 \add back again\add*,
\q1
\v 9 God's breathВҰ233247 \add causes\add* them to perishВҰ233249,
\q1 and with a snort of his nose they comeВҰ233252 to an endВҰ233252.
\q1
\v 10 The lion roars and the UNKNOWN-lion soundsВҰ233256 his voiceВҰ233256,
\q1 AND the teethВҰ233258 of the youngВҰ233259 lionsВҰ233259 are brokenВҰ233260.
\q1
\v 11 The UNKNOWN-lion \add starves to death\add* because of a lack of prey,
\q1 andВҰ233267 the lionesses cubs are scatteredВҰ233269.
\b
\q1
\v 12 \add Now\add* a messageВҰ233272 was broughtВҰ233273 secretlyВҰ233273 to me,
\q1 andВҰ233271 my ears caught a whisperВҰ233276 of it.
\q1
\v 13 When troubled by thoughtsВҰ233279 from dreams inВҰ233282 the nightВҰ233281,
\q1 when peopleВҰ233286 have fallen into deep sleepВҰ233283,
\q1
\v 14 I was hit by fear and tremblingВҰ233290вҖ”
\q1 my bonesВҰ233292 were shaking with fright.
\q1
\v 15 A spiritВҰ233295 passedВҰ233299 over my faceВҰ233298,
\q1 andВҰ233295 the hairs on my bodyВҰ233302 \add stood on end\add*.
\q1
\v 16 It stoodВҰ233304 stillВҰ233304, butВҰ233306 I didn'tВҰ233306 recogniseВҰ233308 what it was.
\q1 There was an image in front of my eyesВҰ233312.
\q1 It was silent and then I heardВҰ233315 a voiceВҰ233314:
\q1
\v 17 вҖҳCan a mortal \add human\add* be innocent beforeВҰ233318 GodВҰ233318?
\q1 Can a personВҰ233317 be more pure than the creator of people?вҖҷ\f + \fr 4:17 \ft All speech marks in Bible translations are added by the translators. It's not certain from the text whether or not this was what вҖҳthe voiceвҖҷ said, and if it is (as we assumed), it's not clear where вҖҳthe voiceвҖҷ stopped speaking and Elifaz resumes. (Many translations put it at the end of the chapter, but remember that chapter breaks are also rather arbitrary and not in the original manuscripts.)\f*
\q1
